Author-Name:   Pham, Michel Tuan
Author-Name:  Avnet, Tamar
Title: 
 Ideals and Oughts and the Reliance on Affect versus Substance in Persuasion.

Journal: Journal of Consumer Research
Pages: 503-18
Issue: 4
Volume: 30
Year: 2004
Month:  March 
Abstract:

 Motivation research distinguishes two types of goals: (a) ideals, which
 relate to people's hopes, wishes, and aspirations, and (b) oughts, which
 relate to people's duties, obligations, and responsibilities. We propose
 that, in persuasion, the accessibility of ideals increases consumers'
 reliance on their subjective affective responses to the ad relative to the
 substance of the message, whereas the accessibility of oughts increases
 consumers' reliance on the substance of the message relative to their
 subjective affective responses. This phenomenon is accompanied by a
 relative change in the perceived diagnosticity of the two types of
 information under accessible ideals versus oughts a change that can be
 related to the distinct modes of self-regulation that ideals and oughts
 trigger. The phenomenon appears to be unrelated to the kind of change in
 depth-of-processing posited by the Elaboration Likelihood Model and the
 Heuristic-Systematic Model.


